How is a star formed



> assistant
- In a cold, dense patch of a giant molecular cloud, gravity overcomes pressure (often triggered by shocks from supernovae or spiral-arm compression).
- The region collapses and fragments into dense cores; as it collapses, it heats, but dust cooling lets the collapse continue.
- Conservation of angular momentum forms a rotating accretion disk; magnetic fields drive bipolar jets that shed angular momentum.
- A protostar grows at the center by accreting from the disk/envelope.
- When the core reaches ~10 million K, hydrogen fusion ignites (pp-chain or CNO), balancing gravity: the star enters the main sequence.
- Winds/radiation clear the surroundings; the leftover disk can form planets.

